               <msContents>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">
                     <rubric>Nomina sacra; name of the ruling king; names of the donors; incipits and headings of the texts; directives for the ministers; most of the abbreviations; part of the musical notation signs above the lines; elements of the punctuation signs and Ethiopic numbers.&#xD;
&#xD;
The incipit parts of most of the texts are written alternately in red and black lines (s. fols. 5ra-rb, 89va-vb, 92va-vb, 104ra-rb, etc.).</rubric>
                     <incipit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </incipit>
                     <explicit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </explicit>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
                  <!--The data in the items below refers to other items. please remove this items and move the information to the appropriate place.-->
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i2">
                     <note>Within Text I, the constituent texts are placed in the following sequence: I-a) Ṣälotä kidan zä-śälästu gizeyat “Covenant Prayer of the Three Hours” (fols. 5ra-8ra); I-b) Mästäbqwǝʿ “Supplications” (fols. 8ra-13rb); I-c) Zä-yǝnäggǝś zä-Yared (fols. 13rb-21ra); I-d) Ṣälot laʿlä nǝwayat ḥaddisat “Prayer over the Sacred Vessels” (fols. 21ra-22rb).</note>
                     <note>In the heading of text III-6, St. Athanasius is called “a brother of Gregory” (most probably, this epithet was mistakenly transferred here from the Anaphora of St. Basil).</note>
                     <note>Parts of the text are written in compressed script (s. fol. 79rb, 134vb, etc.). This was evidently done to fit the text into the space provided by a specific folio.</note>
                     <note>Text III-14 is written in smaller, thinner and finer letters than the rest of the texts.</note>
                  </msItem>
